x4freetext: Targets of the enriched isotope of 74Ge (with 98.9%
enrichment)were prepared by the vacuum evaporation
technique, wherein the 74Ge material was deposited on
circular aluminium foils of thickness 1.14 mg/cm2
spread over a circular area of diameter 15 mm.
The thickness of the target material 74Ge deposited on
aluminium backings was found to be between 80 to
270 mu-g/cm2.
100 cm3 HPGe detector, coupled to a PC based
data acquisition system was used to record the
spectra of residual -activities induced in individual
activated foils. The irradiated targets were
positioned in front of the detector in a particular
geometry so as to achieve a dead time of less than 10%.
a PC based data acquisition system
was used to record the spectra of residual-activities
induced in individual activated foils.
The excitation functions (EFs) of the following
nine reactions: 74Ge(16O, 4n)86Zr, 74Ge(16O,
p2n)83Rb, 74Ge(16O, p3n)82mRb, and 74Ge(16O, 2
3n)79Kr measured with ion beams between 60.2 and
Theoretical estimates of the cross-sections are
obtained using statistical model based code PACE-2
that uses the Monte-Carlo simulation technique
for the de-excitation of a compound nucleus. The
optical model parameters for the emitted particles
, and the average
gamma transition strength are taken from the
systematics.
Various factors likely to introduce errors and
uncertainties in the present cross-section measurements
and their estimates are:
Estimation of the error in the number of
nuclei present in the sample were adopted
non-uniform deposition method and transmission
method. The non-uniformity in the target material
thickness introduces an error of less than 2%.
Fluctuations in the beam current has
been measured by taking the weighted average of the
beam current, and is estimated to be less than 6%.
Estimation of error in the geometry
dependent detector efficiency calculated by
measuring of efficiency using standard source
152-Eu, efficiency calculation were estimated to be
less than 5%
The dead time in the pulse processing
electronics may lead to a loss in the counts by
adjusting the sample-detector distance, the
dead-time correction has been minimized, that is
below 10%.
Errors due to a decrease in the oxygen
ion beam intensity because of scattering while
traversing through the stack are estimated to be
less than 1%.
